That&#x27;s actually a nice trick.  I just hope the compiler doesn&#x27;t complain about it.  I&#x27;ll have to try that sometime.<p>EDIT: just tried it.  The following works:<p><pre><code>    #include <stdio.h>
    int main(void)
    {
        int array[100];
        int *shifted_array = array - 1980;
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
            array[i] = i;
        for (int j = 1980; j < 2014; j++)
            printf(&quot;shifted_array[%d] = %d
&quot;, j, shifted_array[j]);
        return 0;
    }</code></pre>

Simple transformation:<p><pre><code>  for (unsigned i = strlen(s); i > 0; --i) {
    if (s[i - 1] == &#x27;.&#x27;) break;
  }
</code></pre>
Easy to see that s[i-1] does not underflow the array due to the loop invariant i>0. It&#x27;s usually easy to convert signed iteration code to unsigned and when I see this, I can tell the author spent the time to consider what happens at the limits of their inputs.
